The Telegraph - Calcutta
 Saturday, September 21, 2002 				Metro Recommends
				 																THE CD				 																																	(David Bowie)				 																																	lThe master songwriter is back with a bang, churning out a gem, which stands out in the flush of modern mediocrity. The broad-canvas texture, often Floydesque in feel, is accentuated by Tony Viscontis powerplay on bass				 																THE CONCERT				 																																	(Uttam Mancha, Sept. 25, 6.30 pm)				 																																	lThe experimental Bengali band on Rabindrasangeet will render Tagore songs in its own, inimitable style. The nine-member cast of Samay believes in spreading the rich poetry and melody of the bard to the younger generation through their unique sound				 																THE FILM				 																																	(Monday, Nandan III, 6 pm)				 																																	lDirected by Jean Renoir, the film is set in Bengal of 1951. Told through the eyes of Harriet, the daughter of a jute factory manager who grew up in India, the film is a tapestry of post-war India				 																The book				 																																	(Shaiontoni Bose, Arundhati Dasgupta, Bunny Gupta and Nilanjana Gupta)				 																																	lThe collection gathers oral histories, folklore and urban legends from all parts of the country, and explores the many forms of the supernatural  spirits and brahmadaityas, dakinis and djinns, reincarnations and possessions, forest spirits and shape-changing animals. By turns chilling, tragic and darkly comic
